# Quality Assurance

## Code Quality Checklist

### Python Scripts

- [ ] Follows PEP 8 style guide
- [ ] Type hints used for function arguments and return types
- [ ] Docstrings included for all functions and classes
- [ ] No hardcoded paths (use `pathlib` or relative paths)
- [ ] Functions < ~60 lines; refactor if growing

### Jupyter Notebooks

- [ ] **Kernel Restart & Run All** passes without errors
- [ ] Logical flow: Import -> Load Data -> Analysis -> Plot -> Conclusion
- [ ] No hidden state (variables defined in deleted cells)
- [ ] Markdown cells clearly explain the steps
- [ ] Visualizations have titles, labels, and legends

---

## Experiment Quality

- [ ] Experiments are reproducible (seeds set, versions logged)
- [ ] Experiment metadata logged (model, prompt hash, temperature, dataset)
- [ ] Structured logging format followed
- [ ] No secrets committed; use `.env` for API keys

---

## Testing Minimalism

- For utility modules, add a lightweight smoke test (even if not full pytest suite yet)
- When generating parsers / validators, include an inline `if __name__ == "__main__":` block that demo-runs with sample input

---

## Documentation Quality

- README.md must match actual implementation
- Usage guides must be accurate
- Code comments explain complex logic and concepts
- Prompt templates have metadata sidecars
